## Quiz

?? The while loop in `merge` exits as soon as either `i` or `j` reaches its array's length. Why do we then need the two `extend` lines at the end?
>> The loop stops when one array is fully consumed. The other array still has elements left, and because it was sorted on entry, its remaining elements are all greater than everything already in `result`. The two `extend` calls append those leftovers directly — only one of them does work; the other is a no-op.

?? In the worst case, how many comparisons does merging two sorted arrays of total length $n$ require?
>> $n - 1$. Each comparison commits exactly one element to `result`. After the while loop exits, one element (or more) gets copied via `extend` without comparison. So if everything interleaves, we do $n - 1$ comparisons; if one array's minimum exceeds the other's maximum, we do only $\min(|left|, |right|)$ comparisons.

?? Where does the $\log n$ factor in $O(n \log n)$ come from — the merging or the dividing?
>> The dividing. Splitting the array in half repeatedly creates $\log_2 n$ levels of recursion. At each level, the total work across all the merges at that level is $O(n)$ (each element is touched exactly once per level). So the total is $n \cdot \log n$.
